        <ownedEnd xmi:id="_18_4_1_1b310459_1505839734076_484304_15814" xmi:uuid="aae16d13-4131-4a54-b07c-b23dc20e554a" xmi:type="uml:Property">
          <visibility>public</visibility>
          <type xmi:idref="_18_4_1_1b310459_1505839733816_5890_14651"/>
          <association xmi:idref="_18_4_1_1b310459_1505839733816_315068_14655"/>
        </ownedEnd>
      </packagedElement>
    </packagedElement>
    <packagedElement xmi:id="_18_4_1_1b310459_1505839733474_15192_14049" xmi:uuid="a06b90dd-e321-45e5-89f8-361555905f3f" xmi:type="uml:Package">
      <ownedComment xmi:id="_18_4_1_1b310459_1512638132061_76269_32528" xmi:uuid="a1838058-0bcd-42fc-993d-7981b8b98a2b" xmi:type="uml:Comment">
        <annotatedElement xmi:idref="_18_4_1_1b310459_1505839733474_15192_14049"/>
        <body>This capability enables the representation of interconnections between a connected pair of systems in a collaborative context. A system is divided into logical subsystems as defined using the Breakdowns capability, the boundaries and interconnections between the subsystems may be defined using this capability. These boundaries and interconnections are known as interfaces. An interface is not an entity itself, but is comprised of ports on systems and connections between ports. The systems, ports and connections may all have multiple representations. A port may have many connections, but a connection is only between two ports. &lt;example&gt;A computer has a USB port that is spacial, power and information interface to the computer&lt;/example&gt; &lt;example&gt;The interconnections between an aircraft wing and engine could be modelled with a port on the wing having connections to two different engines, with the two connections being realized by different pylon components. Similarly an engine port have connections to ports on two different wings, showing that the engine can be used on two aircraft, or connections to two ports on the same wing showing it can be used in two different places on the same aircraft.&lt;/example&gt; &lt;example&gt;Examples of different representations are physical representations or behavioural representations&lt;/example&gt; The Figure below provides an overview of this capability. &lt;figuresysml&gt;&lt;id&gt;_18_4_1_1b310459_1578990523560_642599_64773&lt;/id&gt;Overview of the Interfaces capability&lt;/figuresysml&gt;</body>
      </ownedComment>
      <ownedComment xmi:id="_18_4_1_13110319_1512984813667_399345_35840" xmi:uuid="b7606565-b6c0-4869-b48a-264f6919cbf3" xmi:type="uml:Comment">
        <body>Enhancement: need to consider how to manage interfaces where the direction is dependent on the state of the components, (e.g. conduction flow is dependent on which is hotter). Is this distinction managed by a classification of the Connection, and if acausal then the names "from" and "to" are not important, but if "causal" then the names imply the direction of flow.</body>
      </ownedComment>
      <name>InterfaceManagement</name>
      <packagedElement xmi:id="_18_4_1_13110319_1588005882277_951446_71545" xmi:uuid="0069d1be-f1d1-44aa-8a6e-106b6944d246" xmi:type="uml:Association">
        <memberEnd xmi:idref="_18_4_1_13110319_1588005882277_566015_71546"/>
